{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dill_ver02/data/sn91068695/00279559484/1949042801/0164.xml":{"full_text":"THE MARION PROGRESS\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY BY THE\nMcdowell publishing co.\nMARION, N. C.\nI TELEPHONE 64\n\nS. E. WHITTEN, Editor and Proprietor\nJ Entered at the Postoffice at Marion, N. C.,\nas second class matter\nSUBSCRIPTION RATE\nOne year $2.00\nStrictly in Advance\nBASEBALL TIME\nThe great American game of Baseball made\nits debut in Marion Tuesday night of this week\nwhen the Marion Marauders met a team from\nour neighboring town of Morganton.\nBaseball is an outstanding sport and offers\nrelaxation and amusement to our titizens at\nlarge. It offers a splendid attraction to our\nyoung people and is an asset in the use of leis\nure time.\nOtis Broyhill, president of the Marion Re\ncreational association, which sponsors the Ma\nrion Marauders, along with a splendid\ncorp of officials and directors, are to be con\ngratulated for bringing baseball to Marion for\nthe enjoyment of both* young and old.\nPLAY SAFE\n\"Play it safe!\"\nThat's the advise of L. C. Rosser, Commis\nsioner of Motor Vehicles to all children of\nNorth Carolina. i\n\"We don't want to spoil anybody's fun,\" he\nsaid. \"In fact we want to see our youngsters\nhave all the fun there is. But we want to be\nsafe, too.\"\nThree-fourths of the boys and girls five to\n14 years of age who were killed or injured in\nUnited States traffic in 1948 were doing one\nof three dangerous things at the time, accord\ning to the National Safety Council. They were\neither ci'ossing the street between intersections,\ncoming behind parked cars or playing in the\nroadway.\n\"If one of your little friends has been killed\nor crippled so that he can never play games\nagain\u2014well, I guess I don't have to remind\nyou to be careful,\" Commissioner Rosser said.\n\"\"But all of you kids should play it safe\u2014so you\ncan keep on playing.\"\n\"So, please play on the playgrounds or in\nyards well away from traffic. And never play,\nnear the streets. Stay away from alleys, drive\nways and parked cars. You kids are mighty\nquick, you know, and a driver just can't see\nyou beside or behind his car or truck. So keep\nwell away from cars, driveways and alleys.\nPlay it safe.\" j\nFARMERS SUFFER MOST LOSS\nThe annual rate of personal income declin-;\ned $2,500,000,000 in February, according to\nthe office of Business Economics of the Com-j\nmerce Department, which says that \"about\ntwo-thirds of the decline in February came in\nagricultural income.\"\nThe total income in February was at the rate;\nof $217,000,000,000 per year, as compared;\nwith $219,500,000,000 in January. This is a\nslight decrease but it.is somewhat significant\nthat most of the decline was experienced by\nfarmers.\nThe statistics may reveal a trend that will\nnot be apparent to business men for some mon\nths. The farmers, one may assume, have some\ncapital reserve and may be able to continue\nbusiness,- \"as usual,\" until their reserve funds\nare exhausted. Nevertheless, it is a sign to be\nwatched by those interested in the continual\nprosperity of the American, economic machine.\nCertainly, if agricultural income declines\nprecipitately, there will be a decrease in the\nbuying of manufactured goods. When this o#\ncurs, there will be a considerable decline in\nthe jobs and pay of workers.\nNATIONAL FAMILY WEEK\nThe observance of National Family Week,\nMay 1-8, provides a rich opportunity for the\nstrengthening of family life in our own coun\ntry. Jointly sponsored by Protestant, Catholic,\nand Jewish groups, it becomes a great relig\nious festival. Because of its inter-faith nature\nit offers a \"community\" approach for better\nopportunities for all families.\u2014Mr. and Mrs.\nSamuel T. Cushing, Upper Montclair, N. J.\nThis is the time of the year when residents\nof McDowell county are amazed by the beauty\n(and beauties) they see about them.\nIf you want to be highly recommended let\nsomebody else say the word.\nTHE ESSENTIALS OF FIRE PROTECTION\nThe National Board of Fire Underwriters\nmade an engineering inspection of San Francis\nco's f&e fighting facilities and turned in a re\nport. The San Francisco Chronicle then wrote\nan interesting commentary on what fire pro\ntection involves.\n\"The report brings out the fact that a com\nplete fire protection system is more than a fire\ndepartment,\" it said.\n\"It is a water supply and means for efficient\ndistribution of the water to the scene of a blaze.\n\"It is a fire alarm system that will not break\ndown\n\"It is the auxiliaries of the fire department,\nthe police department, the facilities of the tele\nphone company.\n\"It is the construction of buildings, frame or\nbrick, stucco or steel.\n\"It is a system for public education in fire\nprevention.\n\"It is the general hazard of all conditions,\n\nand the total resources of a community that\ncan be mobolized against a fire.\"\niThis definition of fire protection applies to\nJ a village as well as to a city. In the small com\njmunity, naturally facilities will be less exten\njsive and elaborate. But the basic needs\u2014\u00ab-a\nigood water supply, an alarm system, safe build\ning construction, and an educated public\u2014are\nexactly the same. Together, they constitute the\nj weapons that can defeat fire.\nNO SERIOUS RECESSION\nThe Bureau of Agricultural Economics,\nwhich has a good batting average on predic-j\ntions, says that there will be further declines J\nin industrial production, prices and consumer i\nincomes but no serious recession is in sight.\nThe backlog demands \"that carried over:\nfrom the war years\" have practically disap-;\npeared and the \"tremendous demand\" for\nmany consumer goods is slackening. However,'\nno sharp drop in general economic activity!\nseems \"to be in the picture.\"\nThe Bureau expresses the opinion that Fed\neral, State and local governments will spend\nmore money than last yean It notes, however,\nthat savings by consumers are increasing al\nthough consumer-incomes will'be. big enough:\nto support larger spending than in any year'\nbefore 1948.\nReferring to the outlook for farm products,\nthe Bureau says a decline in business activity\nwill mean a weaker demand. Larger farm pro\nduction would cause some further price declin\nes but \"a sharp, over-all decline in farm prices\nis not expected.\"\nSERVICES NOT REFORM SCHOOLS\nTwo enlisted men, convicted of auto theft,\nwere recently placed on probation by a civilian\njudge in Florida, on the condition that they\nremain in the Air Force.\nNo sooner had the word gotten back to the\nOrlando Air Base than officials announced\nthat the men had been given \"undesirable dis\ncharges\" and barred from further service. Ones\nofficer pointed out that some courts have the\nerroneous idea that the Air Force or Army can j\nbe utilized as a huge reform school but that!\nneither intends to harbor criminals or poten-'\ntial criminals and when they are discovered,'\nsteps will be take to give them their discharge.\nThe officers of the Air Corps are entirely;\ncorrect and they speak, we have no doubt, fori\nofficers in all branches of the services. Certain-1\nly, it would be a monstrous custom if judges\nthroughout the land, in sentencing men con-i\nvicted of crime would put them on probation\non condition that they continue in the service\nof their country.\n'NICE DAY'\nThe first crocus is already history. Jonquils\nare no longer mere hope, they are bright fact.\nThe first robbin's fame is lost in the anony\nmity of the red-breasted crowd.\nLittle boys are discovering hourly more and\nmore places where they may not run, or walk\n\u2014or even step, if you please!\nAnd little girls are everywhere.\nThe magnolias are vast candeJabras of pink\nflame, tight buds a&low in the lingering twi\nlight. Forsythia doubles the sunlight in innum-,\nerable gardens.\nThe chipmonk indulges a mocroscopic glut\ntony.\nAcross the fields comes a familiar ctfack, and\na shout, as boys devour every new moment of\nbaseball time. f\nThe sidewalks are marked with chalk in sim\nilarly familiar patterns, and girls stand, one\nfoot held up wondering where to hop next.\nThis is April. Folk in other months, to be\nsure, somtimes stop and smile and say \"Nice\nDay,\" or even say \"Beautiful day.\" But about\nthis time of year they all realize they never half\nmeant it till now.\u2014Christian Science Monitor.\nThe proper way to reply to most arguments\nis to turn again to your own work.\nA compromise, to some people, is an oppor\ntunity for the other side to surrender.\nOUR DEMOCRACY\nMen Women*/Tomorrow\nIn the last so yeaks, the\nDEATH RATE DUE TO COMMUNICABLE\nDISEASES AMONG YOUNG CHILDREN\nIN THE U.S.HAS BEEN CUT $0%\nCfv/\n\u2014For. the record progress wc have made in good health\nAMONG OUR- CHILDREN, WE CAN CREDIT\u2014\nTHE TIRELESS WORK OF OUR. MEOfCAL SCIENTISTS\nIN THE CONTROL AND PREVENTION OF DISEASE\nAND THE DISSEMINATION OF INFORMATION\nSY PUBLIC AND PRIVATE INSTITUTIONS\nINCLUDING INSURANCE COMPANIES.\n-THE WILLINGNESS OF PARENTS TO TAKE\nADVANTAGE OF THE FINDINGS OF\nMEDICAL SCIENCE.\nTHE GREATER AVAILABILITY OF GOOD\nMEDICAL SERVICE TO MORE AND MORE\nOP OUR NATION'S PEOPLE\nAT MO OTHER. T/ME-/N NO OTHER. NATION -HAVE\nCHILDREN HAD SO GREAT AN OPPORTUNITY FOR.\nLONG LIFE AND HEALTHFUL LIVING AS THEY\nHAVE IAI AMERICA TO DAW...\n\u2014CHILD HEALTH DAY-MAY I\nr,\nLooking Backward\nFrom The Progress File*\nV- -J)\nMAY, 4, 1922\nAt the regular meeting of the\ncounty highway commission on last\nMonday the road in upper North\nGove township connecting with Av\nery county was ordered built. It will\nbecome a part of the State High\nway system. The construction of\nthis important line of road will cost\nsomething like $80,000.00; $32,000\nof which will be paid by the state.\nAn order was made by the high\nway commission for the construc\ntion of a link of road from Dysarts\nville to the Rutherford county line.\nThis will complete the road from\nMarion to Rutherfordton.\nA. B. Gilkey, familiarly known\nas \"Uncle Gus\", died at his home\nMonday morning in his 92nd year.\nMr. Gilkey was probably one of the\nbest known citizens of the county, j\nAt the Monday meeting of the j\ncounty commissioners an election\nwas ordered to be held in district\nNo. 3, Marion Township, known as i\nStioudtown district, on a bond is\nsue of $10,000, to be used in the\nerection of a new and modern school\nbuilding.\nJohn Wilson of Nebo was last!\nMonday sworn in as a member of!\nthe board of county commissioners.\nMrs. Mamie White, of Washing\nton, D. C., is spending the week with\nrelatives here. i\nJ. Will Pless, Jr., is building a\nsix-room bungalow on his lot on\nViewpoint Drive.\nNext Sunday the third anniver\nsary of pastor J. T. Bowden's minis\ntry with the First Baptist church.\nThey have been three harmonious\nand successful years.\nMore than one and a half million\nfarm residents took enforced vaca\ntions last year because of accidents.\nOne out of every 17 farm people\nsuffered a disabling mishap during\nthe year.\nJ WEIL-1 00\nfOEClARE'lOOtt)\nLIKE 1 GET\n[AROUND/\nNational Family\nWeek May 1 To 8\nChicago\u2014'President Harry Tru\nman called on the American people\nto \"emphasize the spiritual values\nin family life\" in a letter released\ntoday endorsing National Family\nWeek, May 1 through 8 (Mother's\nDay).\nProtestants, Catholics, and Jews\nwill observe this nationnwide event\nfor the seventh year.\n\"It is difficult to think of a\nstable home which is not undersign\ned with a deep religious faith\u2014an\nimplicit trust in the wisdom of Di\nvine Providence and the guidance\nwhich alone comes from on High,\"\nwrote the Chief Executive.\nThe letter was released here by\nRev. Richard E. Lentz, family edu\nactiion director of the International\nCouncil of Religious Education and\nsecretary of the (Protestant) In\ntercouncil Committee on Christian\nFamily Life.\nGiving his \"wholehearted en\ndorsement\" to the observance, Pre\nsident Truman urged: \"I hope this\nobservance will focus the attention\nof all our people upon the home as\nthe basic unit of our national life.\n\"May God bless and prosper this\ngood work and through church and\nsynagogue guide homemakers, pre\nsent and future, to a nobler, more\nsatisfying family life.\"\nDIAMOND LEGEND\nThe ancient lore that gives us the\nspecific birthstone for each month,\nsays of the diamond, the birthstone\nof April:\n\"She who from April dates her\nyears,\nDiamonds should wear, lest bitter\ntears,\nFor vain repentence flow.\nThis stone,\nEmblem of innocence is known.\nInnocence, repentence, sun and\nshowers,\nThe diamond is the gem to be her\ndower.\"\nThe legend, according to the Jew\nelry Industry Council, is that when\nthe God of the Mines called his court\niers to bring him all the known\ngems, he found them to of many\ncolors and tints and varying hard\nness. He took one of each, crushed\nthem, compounded them, and said:\n\"Let this be something that will\ncombine the beauty of all; yet it\nmust be pure and it must be invinci\nble.\"\nNOTICE OF DISSOLUTION\nOF J B STORE\nA PARTNERSHIP\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN\nthat the partnership of R. L. James\nand Leah Burnette as partners, con\nducting the business of general mer\nchants under the firm name and\ns+vle of J B Store, of Old Fort,\nNorth Carolina, was dissolved by\nmutual consent on April 8, 1949.\nR. L. James and Leah Burnette\nwill collect all debts owing to the\nfirm, and will pay all debts due by\nthe firm.\nThis the 20th day of April, 1949.\nR. L. JAMES and\nLEAH BURNETTE\nformerly doing business as\nJ B STORE.\nECONOMICAL.\nJack Is that your last year's\nsuit you're wearing?\"\nFred Yes, and it's my next\nyear's, too.\nANNOUNCEMENTS\nFOR MAYOR\nI hereby announce myself a can\ndidate for re-election for Mayor ir\u00bb\nthe municipal election to be held on\nMay 3.\nJ. W. STREETMAN, Jr.\nFOR ALDERMAN\nI hereby announce myself as a\ncandidate f<Jr re-election as Alder\nman of the Town of Marion in the\nelection to be held on May 3.\nFRANK GOLDSMITH.\nFOR ALDERMAN\nI hereby announce myself as a\ncandidate for re-election as Alder\nman of the Town of Marion in the\nelection to be held on May 3.\nEDWARD H. ROWE.\nFOR ALDERMAN\nI hereby announce myself as a\ncandidate for re-election as Alder\nman of the Town of Marion in the\nelection to be held on May 3.\nD. PAT DAVIS.\nFOR ALDERMAN\nI I hereby announce myself a can\ndidate for alderman of the Town of\nMarion in the muncipal election to\nbe held on May 3.\nx CLINTON H. NORRIS.\nFOR ALDERMAN\nI hereby announce myself a can\ndidate for election to the office of\nAlderman of the Town of Marion in\nj the Municipal election to be held\nMay 3, 1949.\n0. L. BROYHILL\nFOR ALDERMAN\nI hereby announce myself a can\ndidate for election to the office of\nAlderman of the Town of Marion\nin the municipal election to be held\non may 3, 1949.\nM. W. GORDON.\nFOR ALDERMAN\nJ I hereby announce myself a candi\nI date for election to the office of\nAlderman of the Town of Marion in\nthe municipal election to be held on\nMay 3, 1949.\nJOSEPH L. NOYES.\nFOR ALDERMAN\ni I hereby announce myself a candi\ndate for election to the office of\nj Alderman of the Town of Marion in\nthe municipal election to be held on\nMay 3, 1949.\nARTHUR M. EVANS.\nFOR ALDERMAN\nI hereby announce myself a candi\ndate for election to the office of\nAlderman of the Town of Marion in\nthe municipal election to be held on\nMay 3, 1949.\nI SAM M. YANCEY.\nI\nFOR ALDERMAN\nI I hereby announce myself a candi\ndate for election to the office of\nAlderman of the Town of Marion in\nthe municipal election to be held on\nMay 3, 1949.\nROY MORROW.\nNOTICE OF TOWN ELECTION\nNotice is hereby given that art\n1 election for Mayor and five mem\n1 bers of the Board of Alderman of\nthe Town of Marion, N. C. is here\nby called to be held Tuesday, May\n3rd. G. W. Giles has been appoint\ned Registrar and J. Albert Rader\nand C. R. Craig as Judges of the\nelection. The courthouse of Marion,\nN. C. is the polling place and the\nregistration books will be open for\nthe registration of voters Satur\nday, April 9th, and will close Sat\nurday, April 23rd. Saturday, April\n130th, is challenge day. The polls\nwill open at 6:30 A. M. and close\nI at 6:30 P. M.\nj Notice is further given that all\npersons who desire to become can\ndidates shall file notice of their\ncandidacy with J. W. Streetman,\nJr., Mayor of the Town of Marion,\non or before April 18th, 1949.\nThis the 29th day of April, 1949.\nj J. W. STREETMAN, Jr., Mayor\nTown of Marion.\n1 Attest:\nB. B. Byrd, Clerk.\nEXECUTORS' NOTICE TO\nCREDITORS\nj The undersigned, having aualifi\ned as executors of the Last Will and\ni Testament of Roy Lee McCurry, de\nceased, late of McDowell County, N\u00bb\nC., this is to notify all persons hav\ning claims against the estate of said\ndecedent to exhibit them to the un\nj dersigned at the offices of Proctor\n1 Dameron, Attorneys, Marion The\ni atre Building, Marion, N. C., on or\ni before the 1st day of April, 1950,\nor this notice will be pleaded in bar\n1 of their recovery. All persons indebt\nj ed to said estate will please make\ni immediate payment.\ni This 28th day of March, 1949.\nCarl McCurry and\nNora H. McCurry, Executors,\nj ___\nj Try a Progress wun* act.","height":"31464","width":"20964"}}
